04973nam a22005655i 9780773567948DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735679487 a10.1515/97807735679482doi  a(DE-B1597)655852  a(OCoLC)741349724  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA449b.D57 1998eb 7aPOL0290002bisacsh04a362.1/09711 aSomerville, Margaret A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDo We Care? :bRenewing Canada's Commitment to Health /cMargaret A. Somerville. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSponsor’s Address to the Conference -- tHealth Care at the End of the Twentieth Century: Confusing Symptoms for Systems -- tClinical Considerations in Health Policy -- tEconomic Considerations in Health Care -- tPolitical Considerations in Health Care -- tEthical Considerations in Health Care -- tLegal Considerations in Health Care -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of Canada's preeminent social thinkers, John Ralston Saul, begins the book with a harsh reminder that public policy can be successful only when driven by the humanistic principles which fueled its formulation. Once saving money becomes a goal in itself, rather than "something we do on the side," public policy has little chance of survival. In subsequent chapters introducing the five key areas, Dr. Richard Cruess (McGill) and Dr. Sylvia Cruess (McGill) write on the physician's role in society; the Honourable Bob Rae tackles the political challenges of health care in the consumer era; Professor Raisa Deber (Toronto) looks at the rightful place of economics in health policy; Sister Nuala Kenny (Dalhousie) examines the ethical dilemmas we face; and Professor Bernard Dickens (Toronto) describes how current health care issues are perceived by the law. Other contributors represent a "who's who" of Canada's most highly recognized academics, professionals, and policy-makers. Also writing on clinical practice are Pat Kelly (PISCES), Dr. Terrence Montague (Merck Frosst), and Dr. Hugh Scully (Cardiac Care Network). The Honourable Monique Bégin, Mark Wainberg (International AIDS Society), and Rev. Lois Wilson (Senator, Canadian Parliament) write on politics. Nathalie St. Pierre (Fédération Nationale des Associations des Consommateurs du Québec), Devidas Menon (Institute of Pharmaco-Economics), and Dr. John Wade (Former Deputy Minister of Health, Manitoba) discuss economics. Tim Caufield (Alberta), Maurice McGregor (McGill), and Lesley Degner (St. Boniface Research Centre) consider ethical issues. Marcia Rioux (Roeher Institute), Jamie Cameron (York), and Henry Dinsdale (Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons) deal with the law. Do We Care? is a must-read for anyone involved in decision-making about the future of Canadian health care -- and for all of us who are affected by these decisions. Do We Care? is the result of a conference entitled "Directions for Canadian Health Care: A Framework for Sound Decisions" which was held in Toronto in October of 1998.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical policyxCanada. 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aPolitique sanitairexCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aSomerville, Margaret A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 asaul, John Ralston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iT